quizzes.textContent:
[h1]This[/h1]

Every object in C++ has access to its own address through an important pointer called the [b]this [/b]pointer.
Inside a member function [b]this [/b]may be used to refer to the invoking object.
Let's create a sample class: [code format="cpp"]class MyClass {
 public:
  MyClass(int a) : var(a)
  { }
 private:
  int var;
};[/code]
[note]Friend functions do not have a [b]this [/b]pointer, because friends are not members of a class. [/note]

[h1]This[/h1]

The [b]printInfo()[/b] method offers three alternatives for printing the member variable of the class. [code format="cpp"]class MyClass {
 public:
  MyClass(int a) : var(a)
  { }
 [b] void printInfo() {
   cout << var<<endl;
   cout << this->var<<endl;
   cout << (*this).var<<endl; 
  }[/b]
 private:
  int var;
};[/code]
All three alternatives will produce the same result.
[note][b]this [/b]is a [b]pointer [/b]to the object, so the arrow selection operator is used to select the member variable.[/note]

[h1]This[/h1]

To see the result, we can create an object of our class and call the member function.[code format="cpp" codeId="265"]#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class MyClass {
 public:
  MyClass(int a) : var(a)
  { }
  void printInfo() {
   cout << var <<endl;
   cout << this->var <<endl;
   cout << (*this).var <<endl; 
  }
 private:
  int var;
};

int main() {
  MyClass obj(42);
  obj.printInfo();
}

/* Outputs
42
42
42
*/[/code]
All three of the ways to access the member variable work.
[note]Note that only member functions have a [b]this [/b]pointer.[/note]

